Tobiko.jpg)](/wiki/File:Tobiko.jpg)

[](/wiki/File:Tobiko.jpg "Enlarge")

Tobiko in varying colors, served as sushi

[1]_**Tobiko**_ (とびこ) is the [Japanese](/wiki/Japanese_language "Japanese
language") word for [flying fish](/wiki/Flying_fish "Flying fish")
[roe](/wiki/Roe "Roe"). It is most widely known for its use in creating
certain types of [sushi](/wiki/Sushi "Sushi").

The eggs are small, ranging from 0.5 to 0.8 mm. For comparison, tobiko is
larger than [masago](/wiki/Masago "Masago") ([capelin](/wiki/Capelin
"Capelin") roe), but smaller than [ikura](/wiki/Ikura "Ikura")
([salmon](/wiki/Salmon "Salmon") roe). Natural tobiko has a red-orange color,
a mild smoky or salty taste, and a crunchy texture.

[![](//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Tobiko_on_grilled_Albacore.jpg/220px-
Tobiko_on_grilled_Albacore.jpg)](/wiki/File:Tobiko_on_grilled_Albacore.jpg)

[](/wiki/File:Tobiko_on_grilled_Albacore.jpg "Enlarge")

Tobiko, shown in its natural color, topping grilled Albacore tuna

Sometimes tobiko is colored to change its appearance, other natural
ingredients are used to accomplish the change, such as [squid
ink](/wiki/Squid_ink "Squid ink") to make it black, [yuzu](/wiki/Yuzu "Yuzu")
to make it pale orange (almost yellow), or even [wasabi](/wiki/Wasabi
"Wasabi") to make it green and spicy. Sometimes a serving of tobiko contains
several pieces, each having a different color.[2]

When prepared as [sashimi](/wiki/Sashimi "Sashimi"), it may be presented on
[avocado](/wiki/Avocado "Avocado") halves or wedges. Tobiko is used in the
creation of many other [Japanese dishes](/wiki/Japanese_cuisine "Japanese
cuisine"). Often, tobiko is used as an ingredient in [California
rolls](/wiki/California_roll "California roll").

Frequently, masago ([capelin](/wiki/Capelin "Capelin") or
[smelt](/wiki/Smelt_\(fish\) "Smelt \(fish\)") roe) is substituted for tobiko,
due to its similar appearance and flavor. The smaller size of the individual
eggs is apparent to the experienced diner, however.
